<div class='blog-content'>
<h2><a data-no-turbolink="true" href="wedding-toasts-speeches-tips">Wedding Toasts &amp; Speeches Tips</a></h2>
<div class='article-information'>
<div class='info'>
<p>By</p>
<p class='light-blue'>Sara Jane</p>
<p class='set_padding'>//</p>
February 11th, 2014
<p class='set_padding'>//</p>
<a class="pink-link" data-no-turbolink="true" href="../blog_categories/wedding-tips/blog">Wedding Tips</a>
<p class='set_padding'>//</p>
<div class='twitter-btn-count'>
<a class='twitter-share-button' count='horizontal' data-counturl='https://www.weddingbids.com.au/blog/wedding-toasts-speeches-tips' data-lang='en' data-text='Wedding Toasts &amp; Speeches Tips' data-url='https://www.weddingbids.com.au/blog/wedding-toasts-speeches-tips' data-via='weddingbidsoz' href='https://twitter.com/share'>Tweet</a>
</div>

</div>
<br>
<div class='content'>
<p dir="ltr" style="text-align: center;"><img alt="Wedding Speech" src="https://weddingbids-production.s3.amazonaws.com/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/65/content_wedding-speech.jpg" style="height:200px; text-align:center; width:600px" /></p>

<p dir="ltr">It&rsquo;s not just the best man who can make a speech at a wedding. The Father of the Bride often also gets up to say a little something and these days, anyone is welcome to tap their glass and request to say a few words. If you are unsure of the protocol when it comes to wedding toasts and speeches, then read on to find out the do&rsquo;s and don&rsquo;ts and everything else in between.</p>

<h3 dir="ltr">Why do you want to make a speech?</h3>

<p dir="ltr">Unless you have been asked to make a speech, you need to be very clear about why you want to make one. You won&rsquo;t have all of the time in the world to stand there and talk, so narrow it down, be crystal clear about what your intention is and what your main message is, and ask yourself, does this need to be said in front of everyone? Will it enhance the day if it is? Or can it be said in private?</p>

<h3 dir="ltr">Ask permission to make a speech</h3>

<p dir="ltr">Yep, you need to either ask before the day, so that it can scheduled into proceedings as things do run to a tight schedule, or you need to ask for permission to speak on the day, which you can do by tapping your wine glass, and saying that you&rsquo;d like to make a very quick toast or speech. Keep it short, just get on with it</p>

<h3 dir="ltr">Do it before you are tipsy</h3>

<p dir="ltr">Be sure to make your toast before you are drunk shall we say, because you do not want to wake the next day and cringe at getting overly emotional or saying something silly, and potentially ruining the happy couples day. It&rsquo;s natural to be nervous but if it bothers you that much that you feel the need to drink, then make your speech or toast to whom it is aimed at directly, and in private.</p>

<h3 dir="ltr">Keep it short and sweet. Plan it</h3>

<p dir="ltr">You don&rsquo;t need to spend days or weeks planning it as over planning can actually make you panic and the whole thing will be a disaster. Just relax, but do be sure to make some notes, work out what you want to say, what are your main points? Keep it short and sweet and if you want to make a little card with bullet points on to remind you of what you intend to say then do so. Keep your speech or toast within a couple of minutes if you can as there will be other people wanting to speak too and when the whole toasting and speech part of the day drags on, people tend to get fed up and children run riot.</p>

<h3 dir="ltr">Try to focus on who the speech is aimed at and not YOU</h3>

<p dir="ltr">You are not getting up to talk about yourself and how you feel about it all.Focus on the two people who have got married, and those around them and use your speech or toast as a way to make people feel fabulous. You can tell the Bridesmaids that they look beautiful as the whole day has been about the Bride - this always makes them feel noticed and special. Be positive and congratulate the happy couple and keep it basic, don&rsquo;t get too personal as you may touch a raw nerve and upset someone and this is the last thing that you want to be remembered for</p>

<h3 dir="ltr">Be light hearted but don&rsquo;t be the joker</h3>

<p dir="ltr">You can add some humour into things but don&rsquo;t try and be funny if this is not your natural disposition as you will wind up with egg on your face. Just be yourself. This is the best advice that I can give you. Be YOU. If you get up and try and act like you are at a stand up comedy gig, most people cringe at this. Keep it simple. This is not a performance and you won&rsquo;t come away with a gold star. Chances are, most people won&rsquo;t even remember a speech or toast after it is done, but they WILL remember something that was embarrassing.</p>

<p dir="ltr">Keep in mind at all times what your intention is with making a toast or speech and don&rsquo;t get sidetracked. You want to remain crystal clear at all times and keeping things is short is essential. Just relax and be yourself. People want to see the person that recognise, not somebody trying to be something that they are not. You do not need to &lsquo;impress&rsquo; anyone and if things do not go just as you&rsquo;d like them to don&rsquo;t be scared to laugh at yourself.</p>

</div>
<br>
